data.content:
Here's the xUnit equivalent. The key mappings from the reference:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` | Constructor / `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + fixture's `Dispose` |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |
| `Assert.That(x, Is.Not.Null)` | `Assert.NotNull(x)` |
| `Assert.That(x, Is.EqualTo(y))` | `Assert.Equal(y, x)` |

```csharp
// Fixture class handles one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // was [OneTimeSetUp]
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // was [OneTimeTearDown]
    }
}

// No [TestFixture] — xUnit is convention-based
public class CustomerRepositoryTests
    : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp]
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // IDisposable.Dispose replaces [TearDown]
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- **Per-test** setup/teardown → constructor + `IDisposable`. xUnit creates a new instance per test, so the constructor runs before each test automatically.
- **One-time** setup/teardown → extract to a separate fixture class, reference it via `IClassFixture<T>`. xUnit injects and shares the fixture instance across all tests in the class.
- If setup/teardown is `async`, implement `IAsyncLifetime` (with `InitializeAsync`/`DisposeAsync`) instead.
